Sunny.notes: Features a ii-V in bar ii; simple for improvisation.
Sunny.recommendedversions: Bobby Hepp; West Montgomery; Pat Martino

Sweet Georgia Brown.notes: Dominant movements in 4ths during the A section.
Sweet Georgia Brown.recommendedversions: Django Reinhardt; Nat King Cole; Count Basie
Sweet Georgia Brown.songwriters: Ben Bernie / Maceo Pinkard / Kenneth Casey

S\u2019Wonderful.notes: Often played with a latin feel.
S\u2019Wonderful.recommendedversions: Tony Bennett; Julie London; Fred Astaire

Take 5.notes: A section is a two-chord vamp in 5/4 time.
Take 5.recommendedversions: Dave Brubeck; George Benson; Quincy Jones

Take the 'A' Train.notes: Features an II7 chord in the A section.
Take the 'A' Train.recommendedversions: Duke Ellington; Ella Fitzgerald; Cab Calloway

Tangerine.notes: B section ends with an interesting key change.
Tangerine.recommendedversions: Coleman Hawkins; Ben Webster; Ray Brown; Jim Hall

Tea for Two.notes: B section modulates to C Major; nice use of IV7 for a bluesy feel.
Tea for Two.recommendedversions: Oscar Peterson; Anita O'Day; George Van Eps; Tal Farlow

Tenderly.notes: The Kenny Burrell version exemplifies full, rich archtop tone.
Tenderly.recommendedversions: Ben Webster; Kenny Burrell; Ella Fitzgerald & Louis Armstrong

Tenor Madness.recommendedversions: Sonny Rollins & John Coltrane; Emily Remler; Dexter Gordon

The Lady is a Tramp.notes: Many phrases begin on beat 2 in the A section.
The Lady is a Tramp.recommendedversions: Frank Sinatra; Ella Fitzgerald; Tony Bennett

The Man I Love.notes: Opens with a shift from major to minor; B section modulates to the relative minor.
The Man I Love.recommendedversions: Oscar Peterson; Etta James; Lester Young

The Nearness of You.notes: Features a wonderful ii-V to the IV chord in bar 2.
The Nearness of You.recommendedversions: Ella Fitzgerald & Louis Armstrong; Oscar Peterson; George Shearing & Nancy Wilson

The Way You Look Tonight.notes: B section modulates up a minor 3rd.
The Way You Look Tonight.recommendedversions: Benny Goodman with Peggy Lee; Billie Holiday with Teddy Wilson; Wes Montgomery

There Will Never Be Another You.notes: Features a backdoor dominant (bVII7); sometimes played as a ballad.
There Will Never Be Another You.recommendedversions: Chet Baker; John Scofield; Tal Farlow

There is No Greater Love.notes: Features tritones in the A section; B shifts to the relative minor.
There is No Greater Love.recommendedversions: Chet Baker; Tal Farlow; Billie Holiday

These Foolish Things.notes: B section modulates to the iii minor.
These Foolish Things.recommendedversions: Ella Fitzgerald; Chet Baker; Billy Bauer

They Can\u2019t Take That Away from Me.notes: Often features call and response in the A sections.
They Can\u2019t Take That Away from Me.recommendedversions: Mel Torme; Ruby Braff & George Barnes; Ahmad Jamal

Things Ain\u2019t What They Used to Be.recommendedversions: Oscar Peterson; Jim Hall; Count Basie

Tiger Rag.recommendedversions: Original Dixieland Jazz Band; Bireli Lagrene; Django Reinhardt

Topsy.notes: Riff-based head with a minor blues feel; essentially the tune “Swing to Bop” by Charlie Christian.
Topsy.recommendedversions: Count Basie; Oscar Peterson; Charlie Byrd; Barney Kessel & Herb Ellis

Tune Up.notes: Starts in D Major then shifts to C and Bb Major.
Tune Up.recommendedversions: Miles Davis; Sonny Rollins; Chet Baker

Waltz for Debby.notes: A simple melody with interesting harmonic twists; often misspelled as “Debbie”.
Waltz for Debby.recommendedversions: Bill Evans; Oscar Peterson; Sylvan Luc

Watermelon Man.recommendedversions: Herbie Hancock; Mongo Santamaria; Hank Garland

Wave.notes: Includes an interesting diminished chord in bar ii and beautiful chord movements.
Wave.recommendedversions: Antonio Carlos Jobim; Paul Desmond; Ahmad Jamal

What is This Thing Called Love?.notes: Features minor ii-Vs that resolve to a major chord; listen to “Hot House” for similar changes.
What is This Thing Called Love?.recommendedversions: Charlie Parker; Nat King Cole Trio; Wynton Marsalis

When I Fall in Love.notes: Heavily features the classic I–vi–ii–V turnaround.
When I Fall in Love.recommendedversions: Bill Evans; Chet Baker; Tony Bennett with Count Basie

Willow Weep for Me.notes: B section modulates to C minor.
Willow Weep for Me.recommendedversions: Billie Holiday; The Modern Jazz Quartet; Wes Montgomery

Work Song.recommendedversions: Nat Adderley; Nina Simone; Gregory Porter

Yardbird Suite.notes: Features a backdoor dominant; bridge starts on the iii.
Yardbird Suite.recommendedversions: Charlie Parker; Gene Krupa; Tal Farlow

Yesterdays.notes: Opening 8 bars have a moody minor feel; last 8 bars move in 4ths.
Yesterdays.recommendedversions: Miles Davis; Ella Fitzgerald; Wes Montgomery

You\u2019d be so Nice to Come Home To.notes: The Julie London version exemplifies the impact of a great arrangement.
You\u2019d be so Nice to Come Home To.recommendedversions: Julie London; Helen Merrill; Coleman Hawkins & Ben Webster
